[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(27) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Art not thou a seer?",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The Hebrew is difficult, and must be translated either. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Art thou a seer? ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, with a very slight change in a vowel, as an address, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Thou seer. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Zadok is so called because he was now in some sort to fulfil the office of a prophet in guiding David’s course, and also in making known to him the events taking place in Jerusalem which would show God’s will concerning him. Nothing is said in any part of this narrative of Nathan and Gad, both of whom were certainly still living (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 24:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2Samuel 24:13-14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Kings 1:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Your two sons with you.—Zadok only has been mentioned, and probably Abiathar was not present at the moment, but David shows by this way of speaking that he means to address them both.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Your two sons with you.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Zadok only has been mentioned, and probably Abiathar was not present at the moment, but David shows by this way of speaking that he means to address them both.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:27",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Samuel 15:27",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Art thou not a seer? Return into the city in peace ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— “It should seem from hence,” says Delaney, “that Zadok was a prophet: however, as a priest, he was a teacher; and as such, bound to stay with his people in the greatest exigencies, and instruct them in their duty: besides that, by staying to do his duty to his people, he might also do good offices to his prince.” Indeed, the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ראה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "roeh, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "here rendered ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "seer, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "means also a ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "seeing, discerning ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "observing ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "man: an interpretation which suits well with the present state of David’s mind and affairs. As if he had said, Thou art a wise man, fit to make observations on what is passing in Jerusalem, and to give me information thereof. Accordingly David concerted a plan, both with Zadok and Abiathar, of corresponding with him, and sending him intelligence of all his enemies’ measures by their sons, Ahimaaz and Jonathan.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
